I think with this game it's the random map and well-distributed jumpscares and monsters that give you a sense of hopelessness, because many games have one path that's distinctly different whereas in this one, they all feel wrong.

I would have to say that the scariest part of this game is it's lack of direction. If you think of some of the scariest games Mark has played- Slender, Dreadhalls, Vanish, Dungeon Nightmares, Neverending Nightmares: One of the largest correlations is an open-map style game with a 'survive the night' or 'get out of here' or even don't have an objective for a large portion of the game. A lot of these games are randomly generated as well. The dynamic style and addition of literal choice forces the player to take responsibility for their choices.

For instance, I don't get scared in horror films or many other liner horror games because tell myself "This is what I have to do, no matter what I can't change what is happening all I have to do it complete the objective." whether that be killing zombies, moving through the maze or closing doors to stop animatronics from getting in. But with these games, it's just about pushing through. You could have no idea how far you are to the end or if you are walking directly to your doom.

But that's just my opinion.

I have a theory (well, more of a headcanon but weâ€™ll go with it) that connects the events of WKM with Heist, Date, and eventually Heist 2:

After betraying all of his friends and losing everything he has, Actor Mark is trying to find a new way of life. He wants to have fun, but he needs a companion. All of the people he knew, he hates, except for one - us. Also referred to as â€œY/Nâ€, â€œthe audienceâ€, â€œthe viewerâ€, or â€œthe district attorneyâ€, we are the only person that Mark doesnâ€™t have a personal vendetta against. So what does he do? He uses the knowledge he obtained from experimenting with the house to free us from our place in front of the mirror.

With a companion, he now needs something to do. A way to have fun while still boosting his ever-increasing ego. So what does he do? He goes on riveting adventures with his new â€œfriendâ€. We meet interesting people, break out of jails, get deserted on islands, try to survive the zombie apocalypse, meet aliens, and so on. But thereâ€™s still an issue; we know what Mark did.

So in order to gain our trust, Mark pretends to be likable. He takes us to dinner, falls down a pit so we can save ourselves, cares for us when we get hurt, and even takes a laser to the chest when the scientist thinks weâ€™re an anomaly. But itâ€™s all a facade. We cannot be harmed in this world, and if we die, everything resets to a fixed point where we can try it all again. He even pretends to give us (very limited) â€œchoicesâ€, so it feels like weâ€™re more free than we are. However, we can see his true self come through a few times, for example with the â€œMeta endingâ€ in Date, or when he acts like a misogynist saying that he wants to go to the military base because there is a â€œtrusting manâ€.

In these intertwining stories, Mark is the hero of all of it. But, just like the Actor said, every good hero needs a villain. Thatâ€™s where Darkiplier comes in. Whenever we meet, he is trying to tell us that what is happening is all just a game, and that weâ€™re living in Markâ€™s made-up world. But Mark always tries to stop Dark in order to hide us from the truth. Think about it, has Dark ever tried to hurt us? He may seem evil because of his temper and composure, but are his motivations due to genuine malice, or just hatred towards Mark and a need to protect the viewer?

But Dark isnâ€™t the only person who found his way into Markâ€™s stories. Wilford is also a character who interacts with the viewer. But unlike Dark, heâ€™s here for the fun of it. He enjoys Markâ€™s new take on life, and secretly wants to spend time with the viewer to make up for his mistakes in the past.

This theory explains:
-Why Y/N is no longer stuck in front of the mirror
-Why Mark from Date/Heist seems nicer than the Actor
-Why Darkiplier is portrayed as a villain
-Why we see Warfstache in the choose-your-own-adventures
-What Mark did after the events of Damien
-How WKM links to Markâ€™s other projects

TL;DR- Actor Mark saves us from the mirror so he can have a companion to go on adventures (Date/Heist) with. He pretends to be nicer as to gain our trust. He portrays Dark as the villain to 1.Make himself seem more heroic, and 2.Make us think that everything Dark says is a lie in order to manipulate us.

Itâ€™s a little choppy, but I just felt like it was a nice way to link Markâ€™s dramatic projects with his more cheery ones.

As a published author nigh-constantly studying the concepts of storytelling, I thought I'd share some thoughts about Mark's writing style:

Mark's writing isn't perfect. A few interactions could be smoother, some characters fleshed out, and some odd conveniences explained (such as the gardener in Who Killed Markiplier.) That said, he has two things that really set him apart from other storytellers. His methods and his moments. Let me explain.
I have never encountered a plot as bizarre as the Who Killed Markiplier series. This strange, disjointed style that relies on intrigue and confusion to keep its audience engaged... it's all wonderfully refreshing. By itself a good video method does not make, however. This is where Mark's moments come in. He knows how to toy with tension, and how to build to a powerful point. When the music swells, the world softens, and a few lines are skillfully delivered. This is so well done that even in confusion the audience still senses importance. Each video delivers emotion despite not providing any straight answers, and I can honestly say that is no easy feat!

Will it pay off? We'll have to wait and see. Intrigue only sustains for so long, and if Mark can't answer every question he's created satisfactorily, he'll end up collapsing everything in on itself. We saw something similar happen to the TV show, Lost.

Mark asks "who is the opposite of me?" He mentioned before that Dark was the opposite of him, but in what way? Narcissistic, manipulative, and selfish. We've seen Damien, and we know he is not those things. Celine is cutthroat, possibly manipulative, but for what reason? To protect Damien. Was it good? The best idea or method? Most likely, no. But she thinks about someone other than herself.

Consider the actor. So wrapped up in himself, so self-absorbed, that he can't possibly imagine being wrong. Being "the bad guy." Everything is someone else's fault. He is incredibly selfish, only thinking of his own wants and desires. The actor is the true opposite of the Mark we know.

Actor says he needs a villain and that Damien will be perfect for the role. Damien remarks to Celine, rather sarcastically, that Actor should be careful what he wishes for. So, given the choice, what does he do? He becomes the Actor's villain.

"The true villain is the man with the most enemies." Actor made an enemy of Damien and Celine. What better villain could Damien immitate than the one who stole everything from him?

"Darkiplier" is a character. A facade. A role. Damien is playing "Actor Markiplier." The best villain he knows.

Okay, ramble over. Thanks for your time, carry on scrolling.

Each of these games has an absolutely fantastic blend of atmospheric/psychological and shock horror. It's seriously a refreshing scene.
I also really liked the premise of the first game. It sort of, but I couldn't say why, reminded me of an H.P Lovecraft short. The story was essentially that this abominable monster lived in a dark cellar all of his life and had never seen the sun, the grass, or other people, and he spent most of his time reading. I forget how he learned to read but it was something like a caretaker. One day he finds a way to escape and he finally sees the moon, right? Eventually he manages to find a house and a mirror in the light and he finds out why everyone was scared of him: he is a monster and he never knew it. I don't know why but the first and second game really gave me a similar vibe to what I had when I read that story.

The first just felt like a typical "possessed baby" story with mild Lovecraftian elements to it, especially with the whole head spinning around thing on the original night 3, whereas the storybook update leans much more heavily into the esoteric King in Yellow theme they were going for. (BTW, there 6 more souls to save in the updated Escape route, if you wanna get some more secrets to play with. Jack's reactions during this entire game sounds a lot like when a dog person owns a cat for the first time.

You can be the cat and naively bring him where he needs to go, or you can be a mindless sheep following him to your death, OR you can take the path of the rabbit and you can escape. I like that a lot :).

For those who don't know, the baby in this game is based on the being known as Hastur from the Lovecraft universe. Hastur is known as the King in Yellow and is associated with the arts, such as storytelling. It drives artists mad and uses them to disseminate it's symbol, the Yellow Sign, which further enslaves people to its will. Hastur is also associated with a planet called Carcosa, which was once home to a powerful and prosperous civilization until Hastur came and drove it to ruin.

I was also surprised when I found out about the version called the "Bedtime Stories Update" which adds new activities, more souls that you'll need to collect to unlock new features (one of which includes a new container to unlock called "The Doctor's Gift" which must be unlocked in a similar manner to the demon baby's Toy Box), & there's a new attic area with a teaser for what is (I think) new content coming this year! The apartment has also received a makeover so the interior looks more like a house instead of an apartment. Reminder for newbies: Make sure you collect all 6 trapped souls in the demon baby's apartment BEFORE you try to find the 6 new trapped souls on the Escape AKA the "White Rabbit" route! The events of the original 3 nights have also changed enough so that they're worth replaying again even if you've already seen how the 3 nights played out beforehand! To be fair, I think Barry is a tad off-base when he says all characters function the same. Sure, a lot of forward attacks, up airs, whatever you want to say, are similar in function, but characters themselves are very versatile. Little Mac has the charge meter. Olimar has the pikmin. Characters like Kirby have only their body while characters like Marth have disjointed hitboxes with weapons, making priority attacks very different. Link has a ton of projectiles, someone like kirby has none. Some have up air recoveries, some have multiple or super jumps.

It's actually not easy for someone who's mediocre at the game and only plays one character to pick up another character and do well. Not saying Ross didn't do well, but the idea that you can easily play any character with one mindset, is wrong.

Still a great video. Actually found it funny when there's a 15 second silence because they just get lost in the game. Enjoyable to watch!

I actually like the style of the Disney 60's - 80's xerox style. Â It's rough around the edges and you can sometimes see the rough linework before cleanup. To me it adds more character and feeling to a drawing instead of it being so clean that it actually ends up "stiffening up". Â Some animators used to say that their rough work would go to the clean up artists to get stiffened up, because the clean-ups tend to take away some of the added nuances that the rough artists did, by being so model driven and it would also take away from some of the animation because a drawing might employ an animation technique which would break model to pull off something.

My grades are great; it's not anything I'm struggling on, but I want to be an animator. I have barely touched animation softwares, but I know inside that it's what I want to do. I've got so many ideas that I believe are good, but I keep telling myself that "School comes first."

I also have games that I want to play with friends; in your analogy you said "scrolling through TikTok" and it's the same thing. I play games with friends for immediate gratification, whereas animating takes time to get that feeling. I always try to do something whenever they're not online; that's my window of time. If I try to get creative while they're online, I can feel their pull and decide to hop on. I'm not addicted to games, but when down to 2 choices, between playing games with friends and learning animation, I keep choosing the games option, and every single night I feel guilty that I didn't do squat with animation. I choose to do that instead of practicing 3D animation, or practicing how to draw. It's a loop I am in, and like I said, every night all the productivity I built up for animating hits me in bed.

I'm telling myself that I must take a course during any breaks that pop up, and play games with the boys on weekends, and hopefully that objective will be fulfilled. I want to create things. I want to create my own characters, my own stories, my own everything. But I need to start, AND commit, and both of those things are notoriously hard to do with any hobby/career.

A T-rex can only be tamed when it is fully mature (10 Minecraft days). First, you must keep beating down the T-rex until it is unconscious and sleeping. The T-rex will only stay sleeping for 30 seconds. After that, it will collapse and die. While it is sleeping you have to right click it with a scarab gem. The T-rex will wake up fully healed and no longer have red evil eyes. You can also ride the T-rex.

Achilles had been reluctant to acknowledge Shay's correctness until he personally laid eyes on the artifact. Both the Assassins and Templars believed the temple contained what seemed to be an "ordinary" artifact, possibly an Apple of Eden. There's even a moment when Liam questions Achilles, asking: 'Is this the Apple?' as they look at the artifact. Inside the Temple, Achilles eventually admits that Shay is right and intervenes to prevent Liam from shooting him, finally realizing his mistake and showing a willingness to FORGIVE Shay (a contrast to Liam, who understandably succumbed to rage after witnessing Shay's actions that led to the demise of his friends and the destruction of their brotherhood; I also believe this is what led to Shay showing Achilles mercy, and the points Shay made were just to convince Haytham, which worked).

Liam's line stands out to me: 'I hope that world is a good one.' He tries to make Shay contemplate the consequences of his actions â€“ while he did stop the precursor crisis, he inadvertently granted ultimate power to the Assassins' greatest enemy, the Templar Order.

Both sides have their flaws. Rogue's tragedy is a result of a giant misunderstanding and poor circumstances. Achilles changed after his entire family died, and Shay was being heckled by Chevalier (among other things), which caused him to change his view on the Assassins. Then, after the journey back from Lisbon, he decides to choose (to me) the worst possible course of action and betrays the Colonial Assassins, subsequently wiping them off the face of the Earth.

In an ideal world, Achilles would have handled the tremendous amount of grief, and Shay would have calmed down during his transoceanic journey. The two could then have a conversation and realize the risks that investigating the Voynich Manuscript Temples brought, leading them to change the Brotherhood for the better.

I think Rogue has my favorite Ezio's Family arrangement. Great playthrough! One of the things I appreciate about this game is the WEIGHT each assassination has on Shay. Killing people, even bad people, should be hard for a good person. Is Shay a good person? I don't know, but I think he tries his best to be in his own flawed way. Excited for Unity!!

I think the thing that this game was trying to tell us was: not all Templars are bad and not all Assassins are good
Achilles says he won't forget what happened but the world will. By not telling Connor I think he's keeping his word by not passing on the information that he knew even to other assassins.

A lot of people like to complain about this game that they effectively just title swapped the Templars and Assassins, but I think that's kind of the point.

We've always seen this conflict from the perspective of the Assassins. But think about how our actions in-game would look from the perspective of the Templars, who also think they're doing the right thing.

Hooded figures stalking the streets under their noses, slaughtering their coworkers and superiors, always afraid that a simple bump on the street with a stranger could be your last action in life. Using poisonous gases and injectable toxins, or simply bombarding their victims with knives, bullets or explosives. We (the character) essentially are terrorists, just ones who we (the player) know are doing the right thing because it's a video game.

It's not a flattering look. And it isn't helped when, occasionally, an Assassin brotherhood loses their way like Achilles' had. Suddenly, they're just terrorists, without the 'protagonist morality armor' behind them.

One thing I like about Rogue is how it bridges the gaps between AC3, AC4, and AC Unity.
Adewale's conversation with Haytham about Edward in particular was an awesome moment.

When Connor came to Achilles to study, he didn't say anything about the Neck. Because Achilles no longer considered him a traitor, but believed that the assassins betrayed him when they did not listen to what he was talking about. Because of the earthquake that happened in Lisbon, Shay just went crazy. After that, he decides to stop the assassins and thereby atone for the destruction of the city and the dead people. As a result, he became a Templar and helped them take power in the American colonies. But Shay, before going over to the side of the Templars, logically did not think that if the Templars had found this temple in Lisbon first, then the same earthquake would have happened, since they were also looking for temples. If Shay had just calmly told what happened in Lisbon, and not attacked Achilles and other assassins with accusations, then there would have been no assassin deaths. Achilles and the other assassins had nothing to do with it at all. They thought that the Apple of Eden was there, so they did not stop searching, but continued to search.

When Shay Cormac killed Charles Dorian, he found the box, he began to travel the world and look for artifacts. During this, he had a family and for this he was not surrounded by Connor. Later, his son and grandson followed in his footsteps and also became Templars.

Modern Templars, through the memoirs of Shay Cormac, found out that the Assassins do not really want freedom, but order, and the Templars represent the highest order. It can be said that on behalf of the Templars, the Assassins bring chaos, and on behalf of the Assassins, the Templars bring chaos. It says, but that the Assassins and Templars personify order and chaos. Everything depends on their actions. This theme will be explored more in Assassin's Creed: Odyssey.

At the end, the nameless Abstergo analyst becomes a Templar, and the nameless Abstergo analyst who was in Assassin's Creed 4: Black Flag quit Abstergo, and the Templars hunted him down and killed him because he leaked information to the Assassins.

That is why loyal GOW fans who played all the original series can feel the emotions and understand the references in GOW4 (2018). When we see the Blades of Chaos in GOW4, we all legit shed tears. "You're as beautiful as the day I lost you" is the first thing I said when I saw the Blades and later got to use and flex them on the Hel-Walkers. Most people thought it's the Blades of Exile from GOW3, but no, it was the ORIGINAL Blades of Chaos that Ares bound and seared unto his flesh and then later ripped out from him all the way back in GOW1. I understood the references and I knew why Kratos hated those Blades. Still, in GOW4, the Blades finally redeemed itself. When in GOW1 Kratos used it to slaughter his first family, now in GOW4 he is using it instead to save the only family he had left. It is almost poetic

But Odin hung himself from the World Tree and stabbed himself letting the blood drip into the Well of Destiny. Killing himself so that he could enter Helheim. I would like to point out the fact that it's been 20 years since anybody could have a kid in the half life universe. That means most adults that survived the invasion are incapable of creating children. So that means only the people who grew up in this world are capable of having kids. The human population is probably extremely depleted at this point. Especially with many humans joining the combine overwatch in order to survive, and the seven hour war probably killing the majority of the population of earth. With all that said, I don't think it's unreasonable to ask people to consider having kids at the time. Especially if the Combine can eventually reactivate the Suppression Field. All the while not knowing how soon they can.

On the subject of Kleiner's speech (this isn't a spoiler but just in case)

The reason the Nazis were probably so advanced in this time line is because they were. Kind of like the invention of the first rocket. The V1 V2 first war rockets that were already flying to the coast of Britain. That was unimaginable at the time. The Nazis and the German technicians consistently exceeded what was considered impossible with their technology. Which leads back to the work and perfectionist mentality of the Germans. Germany was called the land of poets and thinkers. That's really how it was known. I don't know why almost nobody knows about it anymore. But if you look at the inventions and poets of the Germans, you can see why. The first car, first computers, telephone, jet engine.

The simple reason why the Nazis have the atom bomb in this timeline is probably that the German scientists who invented the atom bomb in America had to stay in Germany. People like Albert Einstein. Thus, the Nazis were able to develop the atomic bomb first. To this day, historians are undecided on how close the Nazis got to the atomic bomb. In fact, the Nazis were close to development even WITHOUT the important scientists who then fled to America. But only in theory. The big problem was the resources. The Nazis fought against all major powers at the same time and therefore had no resources with which to build the atomic bomb. The resources, with the stupidity of Hitler and the high command, were ultimately the decisive point why the Third Reich fell. They had the strength, engineering and tactics. Strongest army in history. But Because of their own stupidity and greed, they fell. I wish Stauffenberg had made it...

The developers did release a request from their Twitter about not wanting to have spoilers revealed due to the game's earlier release in Europe and Australia, so maybe there were some removals due to this, but I have not been able to confirm that, either.

I've heard it mentioned on more than one occasion that some who are concerned about these issues will only be streaming on Twitch, although I can find no information as to why they either feel that is a safer platform, or if they merely have less concern about their Twitch channels.

You were wondering how long had elapsed between games in the Uncharted series, and in particular (I think) how long from Uncharted 3 to Uncharted 4? At one point I played through the entire remastered series as well as U4, making notes when I found clues. It's a bit long but here goes:
"The backstory for Elena and Nate, between the end of Uncharted one and their encounter in Uncharted 2, can be found in Drake's U2 journal. Start by looking below Elena's picture (and the flower) to find "Elena F. / Papua Jul 2006", with a presumably fake phone number: (720) 526-192.

Revelatory details - like other dates and places in Nate's journal - tell a story: Chloe is on the same journal page as Nate's other significant others, including a Cassandra S. - obviously not Nate's mother, who was Cassandra Morgan, but interesting in the light of U4. Looks like Chloe Frazer was in Tulsa in 2002; and she, like all Nate's girlfriends, had a flower pressed to the page, even though she's not a flowers and chocolates kind of girl. (Nate, you are such a cad. But Elena had the freshest yellow bloom.)

People don't seem to realize it but tracing the entire Uncharted timeline can be done with morsels like that. For example: The last date I found was the wall calendar hanging behind Nathan in Jamieson's office, at the end of Uncharted 4. It shows that last scene was in November 2015, about when the game was released; and if daughter Cassie is around 12, that places the epilogue of U4 around 2028. (Elena sure had a long-lived Playstation 1, still running with no bit-rot.) Those journals tells all sorts of little stories for those with the patience to look.

Generally, the games are set in in the year of release. Compare again in Uncharted 2 above where Nate is leafing through his journal - you can see one Nepal visa was issued 29 November 2008 for fifteen days (till 13 December 2008), that he departed 6th December 2008, subsequently went to Indonesia with a visa dated 2009, then wound up again in Nepal at game time in June 2009, that is, 06/09 - as seen on the credit card receipt issued to the Kathmandu medical centre. It mentions AMS and explosive diarrhoea. (Poor Nathan!)

This game is a masterpiece. People keep saying Joel deserved better. Did he really?! Joel was never heroic. We rationalized his actions in the first game and created a heroâ€™s mythology for him because thatâ€™s the nature of video games. That hospital scene at the end of Part 1 was an act of pure evil. No matter how you cut it. That was the moment Joel went from lovable father figure willing to do anything to protect his â€œdaughterâ€ and the memory of his biological daughter to a villain. And the fact that Ellie reveals in Part 2 that SHE ACTUALLY WANTED TO DIE, makes it even worse. In video games the quest is usually to â€œsave the worldâ€. In The Last of Us Part 1 we ended up realizing we played as a character who at the end stop the world from being saved in a selfish act (that we admittedly empathized with because we experienced the heartbreak of Joel losing his daughter and the incredible bond he developed with Ellie. That STILL doesnâ€™t justify what he did. Not only did he murder a slew of innocent people, HE STOPPED THE WORLD FROM BEING SAVED.

It turned the entire video game medium on its ears. Brilliantly. And words canâ€™t describe how genius it was for Naughty Dog to give players the â€œchoiceâ€ to shoot the doctor or not at the end. I always thought that was ingenious. Man oh man The Last of Part 2 letâ€™s us see just how GENIUS it was. Violence begets violence, karma is cyclical, and no good deed goes unpunished. Whether we â€œlikeâ€ it or not Joel had it coming. As does most characters in this shitty world of human depravity where THERE ARE NO HEROES. The amount of emotion Naughty Dog was able to illicit from me with The Last of Us Part 2 is some sort of artistic miracle. Pure magic and serenity turns into pure disgust and hatred in seconds in this universe and they balance that dichotomy beautifully. When I first got control of Abby after she killed Joel I wanted to throw my controller at the TV screen. But one manâ€™s terrorist is another manâ€™s freedom fighter. ESPECIALLY in this universe. Whoâ€™s to say Abbyâ€™s revenge wasnâ€™t just as justified as Joelâ€™s or Ellieâ€™s? In a world this bleak, anything goes. The key to making Abbyâ€™s character work was she was actually the FIRST character to realize the destruction her actions was causing and decided to break the cycle. So by the end of the game I loved Abbyâ€™s character and wanted her to find peace just as much as Ellie. The fact that they pulled that off is astonishing. I love her relationship with Owen and the Aquarium sequence was an ingenious set piece that they used to perfection. That being said, they used those moments of serenity against us because the moment they made us have a â€œboss fightâ€ with Ellie as the villain and forced us to choke her out is one of the most gut-wrenching sequences Ive ever witnessed. In a game of movie. First time in my life I was â€œscaredâ€ to press a button on the controller. I didnâ€™t want any part of it. AND THATS THE POINT. The Last of Us Part 2 is the greatest deconstruction of violence and itâ€™s consequences ever made. In any medium. Period.

Tuxedo + Siamese = Tuxedo
Ginger + Tuxedo = Ginger
Tuxedo + Ginger = Tuxedo

Pharah-syndrome = when it feels like a hero hasn't got new skins for a while (you know, beside ASP and Qinglong) or has never enough new skins regardless of the actual reality. Reason: projecting other things to this feeling, like the lack of an animated short (she has a comic though), or sticking to the past when the hero didn't get skins as often as some of the more popular ones (while still getting more stuff than some of the others).

Tracer-syndrome = when it feels like a hero always gets new skins (or has more skins than anyone else) regardless of the actual reality. Reason: overexposure and temporary peaks of the hero's skin-releases (notice: her last event-legendary was actually Graffiti from Anniversary 2017).

Invisible Mei-syndrome = when people don't complain or notice hero's unbalanced and excessive supply in terms of cosmetic updates (has more legendary-skins than Tracer) or game modes (has 2 own festive game modes based around her), or other content like comics or animated shorts. Reason: Mei is bae (and constantly off-meta and has a low pick-rate making her invisible but mostly because Mei is bae)

I'm really glad this game exists... I'm studying nursing and I've never had myself a panic attack so this  helps me to understand a little how those people feel when having crisis and how I can help them better. <del>i hope this makes sense because i'm not a english native speaker</del>

As someone who suffers from severe social anxiety and panic disorder I can say that this is nothing like the real deal and I didn't get "triggered" at all. But I'm very glad someone out there is trying to raise awareness for mental disorders :)
I'd just like to thank you for the trigger warning. Thanks for being considerate.

Thanks for the warning; I decided to watch anyway cause of curiosity, but it's nice of you to put a warning there. I'm really glad that games like this exist; it means a lot to have them try to explore mental conditions, and this one did make me feel kind of uneasy, I have to say. The flashing of negative worries is good detail, and that's something that I can definitely notice with anxiety.

I feel like this kinda made panic attacks seem more annoying than debilitating, but the flooding of negative thoughts was somewhat accurate to mine, and the inability to move.

On a separate note, I though an interesting idea would be to have a game like this that involved interacting with another person, with things like giving you the ability to type a response to them, but whenever you type a letter it has like a 5 second lag.

I didn't think this would bother me but my breathing started to match the breathing in the game and I started to tense up and had to stop watching it. I've been having anxiety attacks constantly this week and this really works. Probably not on everyone, but I'm definitely going to show this to my friends so they can kinda understand it better.

This was an interesting game. Anxiety attacks range in symptoms--anything from lightly stuttered breathing to upchucking your lunch--so I'm not sure it really managed to touch on all of the experiences people with anxiety have. (Being able to replicate the unfocused frustration and aching of shoulders/neck that I personally feel might be a little more difficult to replicate in game form.) Regardless, I think it provides a nice, safe glimpse into the terrible experience for people who have never felt an attack before. It's an ambitious goal to be able to capture an altered mental state in a piece of media so kudos to the creator for having the balls to try.

Yes Suzy exactly this. You keep stopping the breathing when everything is still blurry. The beginning clearly said "It is important to breathe correctly to stay calm."

For those of you who are complaining that this game is boring or that it blows because this isn't how you experience anxiety or panic attacks, you have to remember that every person experiences anxiety differently. If you remember from the very beginning of the game, the creator said that they wanted to share their experience with others. Just because it's not what you experience doesn't mean that this simulation or the way that the creator experiences anxiety isn't valid.

I thought it was a decent simulation, especially since it really can be that hard to focus on your breathing while walking or doing anything else that is supposed to be "natural" for a person to do. This game can also help raise awareness about anxiety and panic attacks by showing just how serious they are and how they can impact a person's day-to-day life.
thank you for including the warnings suzy

I think part of the controls being bad is on purpose, it's hard to work towards your objective while concentrating on your breathing. That said, I agree that this doesn't really mirror a panic attack well, but I can't think of anything better to do so though. My personal experience now that I've grown a lot as a person and left a lot of my self loathing behind is that I will get an intense FEAR with an intense desire to  go somewhere safer, but the worst part to me is that there is no source for the fear, everything is normal and safe and I'm terrified.

You have to keep breathing as you walk. You can go quite a long while without having the attack if you breathe properly. You gotta make sure you get the blue oval bursting out when you breathe to show you're doing it right.
I like the concept and that it's about raising awareness but the experience isn't really that close to real life.  I'd be interested in seeing the concept fleshed out some more.
